{"title_page": "Rabbit haemorrhagic disease", "text_new": "{{Virusbox\n| image = Emd-1933.jpg\n| image_alt = CryoEM reconstruction of \"Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\" (RHDV) capsid. EMDB entry EMD-1933\n| image_caption = [[CryoEM]] reconstruction of ''Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus'' (RHDV) [[capsid]]. [[EMDB]] entry {{PDBe|EMD-1933}}<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Luque | first1 = D. \n| last2 = Gonz\u00e1lez | first2 = J. M. \n| last3 = G\u00f3mez-Blanco | first3 = J. \n| last4 = Marabini | first4 = R. \n| last5 = Chich\u00f3n | first5 = J. \n| last6 = Mena | first6 = I. \n| last7 = Angulo | first7 = I. \n| last8 = Carrascosa | first8 = J. L. \n| last9 = Verdaguer | first9 = N. \n| last10 = Trus | first10 = B. L. \n| last11 = B\u00e1rcena | first11 = J. \n| last12 = Cast\u00f3n | first12 = J. R. \n| doi = 10.1128/JVI.07050-11 \n| title = Epitope Insertion at the N-Terminal Molecular Switch of the Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus T=3 Capsid Protein Leads to Larger T=4 Capsids \n| journal = Journal of Virology \n| volume = 86 \n| issue = 12 \n| pages = 6470\u20136480 \n| year = 2012 \n| pmid = 22491457 \n| pmc =3393579 \n| url = https://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/87867/1/Epitope%20insertion.pdf}}</ref>\n| taxon = Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\n| authority = \n| synonyms = \n| synonyms_ref = \n| subdivision_ranks = Isolates\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=\"Caliciviridae\">{{cite web |title=ICTV 9th Report (2011) ''Caliciviridae'' |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_9th_report/positive-sense-rna-viruses-2011/w/posrna_viruses/253/caliciviridae |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |accessdate=9 January 2019 |language=en |format=html}}</ref>\n| subdivision = \n*RHDV [FRG/89] (RHDV-FRG)\n*RCV [ITL/95] (RHDV-RCV)\n*RCV-A1 [MIC-07/2007/AU] (RHDV-RCV-A1)\n*RHDV [Ashington/1998/UK] (RHDV-Ash)\n}}\n[[File:CSIRO ScienceImage 2009 Rabbit Calicivirus.jpg|thumb|Rabbit Calicivirus <small>CSIRO</small>]]\n\n'''Rabbit haemorrhagic disease''' ('''RHD''') is a highly infectious and lethal form of viral hepatitis that affects European rabbits ''(Oryctolagus cuniculus)''. Mortality rates in adult rabbits generally range from 70 to 100 percent.<ref name=Capucci2017>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Cavadini |first2=P. |last3=Schiavitto |first3=M. |last4=Lombardi |first4=G. |last5=Lavazza |first5=A. |title=Increased pathogenicity in rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus type 2 (RHDV2) |journal=Veterinary Record |date=29 April 2017 |volume=180 |issue=17 |page=426 |doi=10.1136/vr.104132}}</ref> The disease is caused by the [[lagovirus]] '''rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus''' ('''RHDV''') in the family [[Caliciviridae]]. The virus infects only rabbits, and has been used in some countries to control feral rabbit populations.\n\n== RHDV and RHDV2 ==\n\nRabbit haemorrhagic disease viruses (RHDV) are single strand RNA viruses in the genus Lagovirus and the family Caliciviridae. In the course of its evolution RHDV split into six distinct genotypes,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kerr |first1=P. J. |last2=Kitchen |first2=A. |last3=Holmes |first3=E. C. |title=Origin and Phylodynamics of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus |journal=Journal of Virology |date=16 September 2009 |volume=83 |issue=23 |pages=12129\u201312138 |doi=10.1128/JVI.01523-09|doi-access=free }}</ref> all of which are highly pathogenic. In addition, non-pathogenic rabbit caliciviruses related to but distinct from RHDV have been identified in Europe and Australia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Fusi |first2=P. |last3=Lavazza |first3=A. |last4=Pacciarini |first4=M.L. |last5=Rossi |first5=C. |title=Detection and preliminary characterization of a new rabbit calicivirus related to rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus but nonpathogenic |journal=Journal of Virology |date=December 1996 |volume=70 |issue=12 |pages=8614-8623}}</ref>\n\nThe two strains of rabbit hemorrhagic disease currently of medical significance are RHDV and RHDV2. RHDV (sometimes referred to as RHDV1, or as classical RHD) only affects adult European rabbits (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''). This virus was first reported in China in 1984,<ref name=Liu1984>{{cite journal |last1=Liu |first1=S.J. |last2=Xue |first2=H.P. |last3=Pu |first3=B.Q. |last4=Qian |first4=N.H. |title=A new viral disease in rabbits |journal=Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Medicine (Xumu yu Shouyi) |date=1984 |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=253-255}}</ref> from which it spread to much of Asia, Europe, Australia, and elsewhere. There have been a few isolated outbreaks of RHDV in the United States and Mexico, but they remained localized and were eradicated.\n\nIn 2010, a new lagovirus with a distinct antigenic profile was identified in France. This virus also caused RHD but behaved differently from RHDV in that it was able to cause disease in vaccinated and young rabbits as well as in hares ''(Lepus spp.)''.<ref name=Capucci2017 /> All these features strongly suggested that the virus was not derived from RHDV but from some other unknown source.<ref name=Capucci2017 />  The new virus was named rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (RHDV2). RHDV2 is distinct enough from RHDV that the two require different vaccines, which are only partially cross protective. RHDV2 has since spread to the majority of Europe as well as to Australia and Canada.\n\n== History ==\nRabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDV first appeared in the Winter of 1983 in Jiangsu Province of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It was first isolated and characterized by S.J. Liu ''et al''. in 1984.<ref name=Merck>{{cite web | title = A New Viral Disease of Rabbit| work = The Merck Veterinary Manual | year = 2006 | url = http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/171330.htm | accessdate = 2007-06-17 }}</ref> The Chinese outbreak was spread by the [[angora rabbit]], which had originated in [[Europe]]. Fourteen million domesticated rabbits died within nine months in the outbreak.<ref name=IAS>[http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/rabbit_hemorrhagic_disease.pdf Center for Food Security and Public Health]</ref>\n\nFrom China, RHDV spread westward and reached Europe in 1988. The virus has since appeared in Mexico, [[Cuba]], Australia, New Zealand, the United States and Canada.<ref name=Merck/> In 1992, the United Kingdom reported its first case of RHDV in domestic show rabbits. By the late 1990s, RHDV stretched to forty countries and had become [[endemic]] in [[Wild animal|wild]] and [[feral]] rabbit populations in Europe, Australia, New Zealand and [[Cuba]].<ref name=IAS/> In Europe, there was a rapid increase in research into RHD, due to the importance of the commercial breeding of rabbits for meat and fur production.\n\nThe first reported case of RHDV in the United States was in Iowa on March 9, 2000. The affected breeds included [[List of rabbit breeds|Palominos]] and [[Californian rabbit|California Whites]]. By April 6, 25 of the 27 affected rabbits had died of the infection. In order to contain the disease, the remaining two rabbits were euthanized. No new introductions of rabbits were placed on the farm for two years after the discovery of RHDV1 and August 1999 was the last time rabbits left and/or returned to the farm. The United States experienced other outbreaks of RHDV in 2001 ([[Utah]], [[Illinois]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) and 2005 ([[Indiana]]).<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn 2010, a new virus variant called rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (RHDV2) emerged in France.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Le Gall-Recul\u00e9|first=Ghislaine|last2=Lavazza|first2=Antonio|last3=Marchandeau|first3=St\u00e9phane|last4=Bertagnoli|first4=St\u00e9phane|last5=Zwingelstein|first5=Fran\u00e7oise|last6=Cavadini|first6=Patrizia|last7=Martinelli|first7=Nicola|last8=Lombardi|first8=Guerino|last9=Gu\u00e9rin|first9=Jean-Luc|date=2013-09-08|title=Emergence of a new lagovirus related to rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus|journal=Veterinary Research|language=En|volume=44|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-44-81|pmc=3848706|pmid=24011218|pages=81}}</ref> RHDV2 has since spread from France to the rest of Europe, Great Britain, Australia, and New Zealand. Outbreaks of RHDV2 started occurring in the United States and Vancouver Island Canada in 2019. In 2020, RHDV2 has been reported in Washington State, New York, Arizona, New Mexico, and Texas.\n\n== World geographic distribution ==\n===Asia===\nThe first reported outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDV1 occurred in 1984 in the Jiangsu Province of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=Liu1984 />  The outbreak occurred in a group of Angora rabbits that had been imported from Germany. The cause of the disease was determined to be a small non-enveloped RNA virus. An inactivated vaccine was developed from the isolated virus that proved effective in preventing disease.<ref name=Liu1984 /> In less than a year, the disease spread over an area of 50,000 square kilometers in China and killed 140 million domestic rabbits.<ref name=\"Abrantes2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Abrantes|first1=J|last2=van der Loo|first2=W|last3=Le Pendu|first3=J|last4=Esteves|first4=PJ|title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease (RHD) and rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus (RHDV): a review|journal=Veterinary Research|date=10 February 2012|volume=43|pages=12|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-43-12|pmid=22325049|pmc=3331820}}</ref>   [[Republic of Korea|South Korea]] was the next country in Asia to report RHD outbreaks following the importation of rabbit fur from China.<ref name=Abrantes2012 />  RHD has since spread to and become endemic in many countries in Asia, including India and the Middle East.\n\n===Americas (North and South)===\nSince 1993, RHDV1 has been endemic in Cuba; it is also believed to be thriving in [[Bolivia]]. From 1988 to 1992 Mexico dealt with an RHDV1 endemic in domestic rabbits, but was able to quarantine and eradicate the outbreak.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nRHDV1 was unable to establish a foothold in the United States, where ''Oryctolagus cuniculus'' does not occur in the wild.<ref name=IAS/> Species native to the United States [[Eastern cottontail|cottontails]] ''(Sylvilagus floridanus)'', [[black-tailed jackrabbit]]s ''(Lepus californicus)'' and [[volcano rabbit]]s ''(Romerolagus diazzi)'' were not susceptible to RHDV1.<ref name=IAS/> Outbreaks of RHDV1 in domestic populations have occurred in 2000 (Iowa<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit calicivirus infection confirmed in Iowa rabbitry |url=https://www.avma.org/News/JAVMANews/Pages/s051500d.aspx |website=www.avma.org |publisher=American Veterinary Medical Association |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2001 (Utah<ref>{{cite web |title=Viral Hemorrhagic Disease of Rabbits_ Utah 8_28_01 |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_domestic/ct_vhdr_utah0801 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>, Illinois<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Campagnolo |first1=Enzo R. |last2=Ernst |first2=Mark J. |last3=Berniger |first3=Mary L. |last4=Gregg |first4=Douglas A. |last5=Shumaker |first5=Thomas J. |last6=Boghossian |first6=Aida M. |title=Outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease in domestic lagomorphs |journal=Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association |date=October 2003 |volume=223 |issue=8 |pages=1151\u20135 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/9034795 |accessdate=22 June 2019|doi=10.2460/javma.2003.223.1151 |pmid=14584745 }}</ref>, and New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aglearn.usda.gov/customcontent/APHIS/Disposal/FAD/images/rabbitHemo.pdf|title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease (Calicivirus) in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=AgLearn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>) 2005 (Indiana<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease_ Indiana |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_archives/ct_rhdindiana061505 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2008, 2010, and 2018 (Ohio<ref>{{cite web |title=First report of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Type 2 In US found in Ohio |url=https://agri.ohio.gov/wps/portal/gov/oda/programs/animal-disease-diagnostic-lab/news-and-events/Rabbit-Hemorrhagic-Disease-Type-2-Found-In-Ohio |publisher=Ohio Department of Agriculture |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref> and Pennsylvania<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease, United States of America (Jefferson County, Pennsylvania report) |url=http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=28906 |website=OiE |publisher=World Organization for Animal Health |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>). \n\nIn early 2018, the first outbreak of the RHDV2 virus in British Columbia was discovered in feral rabbits on central Vancouver Island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sterritt|first1=Spencer|title=Rare and lethal virus found in deceased Nanaimo rabbits; 1st case in B.C.|url=https://nanaimonewsnow.com/article/570436/rare-and-lethal-virus-found-deceased-nanaimo-rabbits-1st-case-bc|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=NanaimoNewsNOW|date=2 March 2018}}</ref> In July 2019, the Washington State Veterinarian's Office confirmed the first case of RHDV2 in Washington State; the domesticated rabbit was bred on [[Orcas Island]].<ref>{{cite press release |last=McGann |first=Chris |date=19 June 2019 |title=Deadly rabbit disease confirmed on Orcas Island |url=https://agr.wa.gov/about-wsda/news-and-media-relations/news-releases?article=26243 |location=Olympia, WA |publisher=Washington State Department of Agriculture |access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV2 occurred at a veterinary hospital in New York. Thirteen pet rabbits were affected, and all died of the disease. The source of the virus has yet to be identified. <ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease, United States of America |url=https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=33541 |website=www.oie.int |publisher=OIE |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV2 began in New Mexico, Arizona, and Texas that is affecting wild jackrabbit and cottontail populations as well as domestic pet species.  <ref>http://www.wildlife.state.nm.us/rabbit-hemorrhagic-disease-cause-for-rabbit-mortality/</ref> This outbreak is spreading, and is unlikely to be contained. \n\n===Australia===\nIn 1991 a strain of the RHDV1 virus, Czech CAPM 351RHDV, was imported to Australia<ref>{{cite book|title=Australia's War Against Rabbits |last=Cooke |first=Brian Douglas |publisher=CSIRO Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=9780643096127 |url= http://www.publish.csiro.au/pid/6508.htm}}</ref> under strict [[quarantine]] conditions to research the safety and usefulness of the virus if it was used as a [[biological control agent]] against Australia and New Zealand's [[Rabbits in Australia|rabbit pest problem]]. Testing of the virus was undertaken on [[Wardang Island]] in [[Spencer Gulf]] off the coast of the [[Yorke Peninsula]], [[South Australia]]. In 1995 the virus escaped quarantine and subsequently killed 10 million rabbits within 8 weeks of its release.<ref name=strive>{{cite web|url=http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |format=pdf |title=Rabbit Calicivirus Disease (RCD) |last=Strive |first=Tanja |publisher=[[Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]] |date=16 July 2008 |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415081441/http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |archivedate=April 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017 a new Korean strain known as RHDV1 K5 was successfully released in a deliberate manner after almost a decade of research. This strain was chosen in part because it functions better in cool, wet regions where the previous Calicivirus was less effective.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Prue|title=K5 rabbit virus an early success, researchers say|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-04-01/k5-rabbit-virus-an-early-success-csiro-researchers-say/8400816|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn July 1997, after considering over 800 public submissions, the [[New Zealand Ministry of Health]] decided not to allow RHDV to be imported into New Zealand to control rabbit populations. This was backed up in an early August review of the decision by the Director-General of Agriculture. However, in late August it was confirmed that RHDV had been deliberately and illegally introduced to the [[Cromwell, New Zealand|Cromwell]] area of the [[South Island]].\n\nAn unsuccessful attempt was made by New Zealand officials to control the spread of the disease. It was, however, being intentionally spread, and several farmers (notably in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] area) admitted to processing rabbits that had died from the disease in kitchen blenders for further spreading.\n\nHad the disease been introduced at a better time, there would have been a more effective control of the population. However, it was released after breeding had commenced for the season, and rabbits under 2 weeks old at the time of the introduction were resistant to the disease. These young rabbits were therefore able to survive and breed rabbit numbers back up. Ten years on, rabbit populations (in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] in particular) are beginning to reach near pre-plague proportions once again though they have not yet returned to pre RCD levels.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Munro|editor1-first=Robert K. |editor2-last=Williams|editor2-first=Richard T. |title=Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease: Issues in Assessment for biological control |date=1994 |publisher=Bureau of Resource Sciences |location=Canberra |isbn=9780644335126}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Plan for 1080 drops in MacKenzie Basin |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/2441711/Mackenzie-1080-drop-plan |last=Williams |first=David |date=26 May 2009 |newspaper= The Press |accessdate = 2009-06-14}}</ref>\n\nResistance to RHD in New Zealand rabbits has led to the widespread use of [[1080 usage in New Zealand|Compound 1080 (Sodium fluoroacetate)]]. The Government and department of Conservation are having to increase their use of 1080 to protect Reserve land from rabbits and preserve the gains made in recent years through the use of RHD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1080facts.co.nz/ |title=Welcome to 1080: The Facts |publisher=1080facts.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nThe first report of RHDV in Europe came from in Italy in 1986.<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> From there it spread to much of Europe.  Spain's first reported case was in 1988,<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> and France, Belgium, and [[Scandinavia]] followed in 1990. Spain experienced a large die-off of wild rabbits, which in turn caused a population decline in predators that normally ate rabbits, including the [[Iberian lynx]] and [[Spanish imperial eagle]].<ref name=sd110705>{{cite news | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/07/110705081111.htm | title = Iberian Lynx Depends On Rabbits for Survival | publisher = Science Daily | date = 5 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=sa110712>{{cite news | url = http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/extinction-countdown/2011/07/12/deadly-rabbit-disease-may-have-doomed-iberian-lynx/ | title = Deadly Rabbit Disease May Have Doomed Iberian Lynx | first = John R. | last = Platt | work = Scientific American | date = 12 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nRHD caused by RHDV was reported for the first time in the United Kingdom in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chasey |first1=D. |title=Possible origin of rabbit haemorrhagic disease in the United Kingdom |journal=Veterinary Record |date=1994 |volume=135 |issue=21 |pages=469-499}}</ref> This initial epidemic was brought under control in the late 1990s using a combination of vaccination, strict biosecurity, and good husbandry.<ref name=Rocchi2018>{{cite journal |last1=Rocchi |first1=Mara S. |last2=Dagleish |first2=Mark P. |title=Diagnosis and prevention of rabbit viral haemorrhagic disease 2 |journal=In Practice |date=27 January 2018 |volume=40 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201316 |doi=10.1136/inp.k54}}</ref> The new viral strain RHDV2 was first detected in England and Wales in 2014, and soon spread to Scotland and Ireland.<ref name=Rocchi2018 /> \n\nIn April 2016, a highly lethal disease started affecting one of the northernmost feral rabbit populations in the world in [[Helsinki]], Finland. The outbreak has since been identified to be caused by the new RHDV2 strain of the virus, being the first appearance of RHD in the country. Cases of viral transmission to domesticated pet rabbits have been confirmed and vaccinating rabbits has been recommended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evira.fi/elaimet/elainlaakaripalvelut/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille/2016/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille-elokuu-2016/rhd-tauti-todettu-myos-lemmikkikaniinissa-erityisluvallista-rokotetta-saatavilla/|title=RHD-tauti todettu my\u00f6s lemmikkikaniinissa - erityisluvallista rokotetta saatavilla|website=Finnish Food Safety Authority (Finnish)|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n== Transmission ==\nTransmission of RHD occurs by direct contact with an infected animal and [[fomite]]s. Rabbits acquire RHD through oral, nasal or [[conjunctival]] pathways. Urine, feces and respiratory secretions may also shed the virus. The virus may also be carried by the wind. Carriers of the virus may remain infectious for up to a month depending on climate conditions; however, the virus has been known to persist for as little as 2 days and as long as 215 days. An infected carcass or hairs from an infected animal may also transmit RHD. Fomites such as clothing, contaminated food, cages, bedding, feeders and water will also harbour the virus. Even though the virus cannot reproduce in other mammals, predators and scavengers such as foxes, ferrets and some birds can excrete the virus through their faeces after ingesting an infected rabbit carcass. Flies, rabbit fleas, and mosquitoes can also spread the virus between rabbits.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nClimate appears to play a crucial role in the transmission of RHD. In normal conditions, most outbreaks of RHD occur in winter or spring. High temperatures in late spring and summer will considerably reduce the spread of the virus. RHD will also be more prevalent in dry and semi-dry areas than in areas that are relatively cool and humid.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Signs ==\nRHD primarily infects only adult rabbits. In fact, research has shown that rabbits younger than 8 weeks of age are resistant to the virus. The incubation period for the RHD virus is between 1 and 3 days, with death following 1 to 2 days after the infection. There is a wide range of RHD symptoms. Most rabbits will show no signs of external symptoms of RHD.\n\nSymptomatic cases of RHD will display fever, squeals, and often coma leading to death within 12 to 36 hours. In less severe cases, rabbits may display uneasiness, excitement, [[Anorexia (symptom)|anorexia]], swollen eyelids, [[paralysis]], ocular [[haemorrhage]]s, and \"paddling\" or loss of skin. Convulsions may be seen as well. A fatal bloody discharge from the nose has been exhibited along with blood-stained cage floors, though these symptoms may have occurred after death. Rabbits who have recovered from the less severe symptoms usually develop severe [[jaundice]] with weight loss and [[lethargy]]. Diarrhoea, constipation and abdominal cramping are then exhibited right before death a few weeks later.<ref>?</ref>\n\nRHD causes rapid development of [[blood clot]] formation in major organs such as the heart, lungs and kidneys. The clots block blood vessels causing heart and respiratory failure. An infected rabbit that has died from RHD will often have its legs straight out and head over its neck.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nRHD may be indicated when several animals in the herd die after experiencing a fever and lethargy. [[Differential diagnosis]] includes [[pasteurellosis]], [[myxomatosis]], poisoning, heat exhaustion, and ''[[E. coli]]'' or ''[[Clostridium perfringens]]'' type E [[enterotoxemia]].\n\nRabbits that die from RHD are usually in good outward state. However, the most frequent post-mortem lesions are [[necrosis]] of the [[liver]], and [[splenomegaly]]. The liver of RHD rabbits may have a fine reticular pattern of necrosis outline each lobule and maybe yellow, gray or pale in colour. The liver is also usually [[friable]] and swollen. The spleen will be black in colour and also swollen with rounded edges, while the kidneys are dark brown in colour. [[Haemorrhages]] will also be seen many other organs and tissues. The trachea may present a foamy, bloody mucous. [[Enteritis]] of the small intestine and swollen [[meninges]] may also occur.\n\nLaboratory tests such as [[reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction]] (RT-PCR), [[Western blotting]], negative-staining immunoelectron microscopy, and [[ELISA]]s may be performed on samples from the liver, blood, spleen or other organs.\n\n== Morbidity, mortality, and immunity ==\nRHD is extremely hard to locate in the wild since about 75% of rabbits with RHD will die in their burrows underground. Due to this difficulty, the [[morbidity]] and [[Mortality rate|mortality]] estimates for RHD have a broad range. The morbidity rate ranges from 30% to 100% and the mortality rate from 40% to 100%; however, the typical mortality rate is usually around 90%.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn the wild, outbreaks in rabbits vary depending on the season, breeding cycles and geographical location. Some areas will see a high morbidity and mortality among its rabbit populations followed by calmer periods.\n\nMaternal antibodies such as [[immunoglobulin G]] (IgG), which are readily transmitted to the young across the placenta, may explain why very young rabbits are resistant to RHD. Some scientists also believe that the immature immune system of a young rabbit cannot produce the number of chemicals needed to initiate clotting in order to kill. Rabbits may develop immunity against other strains of the RHD virus, while others may endure persistent infections. The immunity does not survive through the next generation, leaving open the possibility of further outbreaks in the population.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marques|first1=Raquel M|last2=Teixeira|first2=Luzia|last3=\u00c1guas|first3=Artur P|last4=Ribeiro|first4=Joana C|last5=Costa-e-Silva|first5=Ant\u00f3nio|last6=Ferreira|first6=Paula G|title=Immunosuppression abrogates resistance of young rabbits to Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease (RHD)|journal=Veterinary Research|date=4 February 2014|volume=45|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-45-14|pmc=3926702|pmid=24490832|pages=14}}</ref>\n\n== Control ==\nCountries that are uninfected by RHD may place restrictions on importation from endemic countries. According to the [[Merck & Co.|Merck]]/[[Merial]] Manual For Pet Health, Home Edition, 2007, RHD is a reportable disease in the United States. If a diagnosis is made by a veterinarian, a notification to the \"appropriate government authorities\" must be made.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nBecause of the highly infectious nature of the disease, strict quarantine is necessary when outbreaks occur. Depopulation, disinfection, surveillance and quarantines are the only way to properly and effectively eradicate the disease. Good disinfectants include 10% [[sodium hydroxide]], 1-2% [[formalin]], 2% One-Stroke Environ, and 10% household [[bleach]]. The RHD virus is resistant to [[ethers]] and [[chloroform]]. Deceased rabbits must be removed immediately and discarded in a safe manner. Surviving rabbits are quarantined or humanely euthanized. Test rabbits may be used to monitor the virus on vaccinated farms.<ref name=\"IAS\" />\n\nThere are several vaccines available against VHD in the UK: Cylap, made by Fort Dodge Animal Health; Lapinject, made by CEVA Animal Health; Anivac, made by Animalcare Ltd and FILAVAC, made by Filavie. All last for 12 months and contain inactivated strains of VHD. A live combination vaccine, Nobivac Myxo-RHD, made by MSD Animal Health, has recently become available. Its active ingredient is a live myxoma-vectored RHD virus strain 009 and it offers a duration of immunity of 1 year against both RHD and [[myxomatosis]].<ref name=\"NOAH Compendium\">[http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html Therapeutic Indication:  For rabbits] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526030329/http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html |date=2013-05-26 }}, National Office of Animal Health rabbit vaccines.{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}.</ref> FILAVAC has been authorised by the VMD in April 2017; it is currently the only vaccine containing both classic and variant strain of VHD virus.<ref>http://www.vmd.defra.gov.uk/ProductInformationDatabase/SPC_Documents/SPC_1170567.DOC</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rabbits in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*New outbreak in Canada reported on Vancouver Island {{Cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/b-c-issues-warning-to-pet-rabbit-owners-as-virus-spreads-to-lower-mainland-1.4587233 | title=B.C. Issues warning to pet rabbit owners as virus spreads to Lower Mainland &#124; CBC News}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Animal_Health_in_the_World/docs/pdf/Disease_cards/RHD.pdf Disease card]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q994732}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease}}\n[[Category:Animal viral diseases]]\n[[Category:Rabbit diseases]]\n[[Category:Hemorrhagic fevers]]\n[[Category:Animal virology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Virusbox\n| image = Emd-1933.jpg\n| image_alt = CryoEM reconstruction of \"Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\" (RHDV) capsid. EMDB entry EMD-1933\n| image_caption = [[CryoEM]] reconstruction of ''Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus'' (RHDV) [[capsid]]. [[EMDB]] entry {{PDBe|EMD-1933}}<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Luque | first1 = D. \n| last2 = Gonz\u00e1lez | first2 = J. M. \n| last3 = G\u00f3mez-Blanco | first3 = J. \n| last4 = Marabini | first4 = R. \n| last5 = Chich\u00f3n | first5 = J. \n| last6 = Mena | first6 = I. \n| last7 = Angulo | first7 = I. \n| last8 = Carrascosa | first8 = J. L. \n| last9 = Verdaguer | first9 = N. \n| last10 = Trus | first10 = B. L. \n| last11 = B\u00e1rcena | first11 = J. \n| last12 = Cast\u00f3n | first12 = J. R. \n| doi = 10.1128/JVI.07050-11 \n| title = Epitope Insertion at the N-Terminal Molecular Switch of the Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus T=3 Capsid Protein Leads to Larger T=4 Capsids \n| journal = Journal of Virology \n| volume = 86 \n| issue = 12 \n| pages = 6470\u20136480 \n| year = 2012 \n| pmid = 22491457 \n| pmc =3393579 \n| url = https://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/87867/1/Epitope%20insertion.pdf}}</ref>\n| taxon = Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\n| authority = \n| synonyms = \n| synonyms_ref = \n| subdivision_ranks = Isolates\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=\"Caliciviridae\">{{cite web |title=ICTV 9th Report (2011) ''Caliciviridae'' |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_9th_report/positive-sense-rna-viruses-2011/w/posrna_viruses/253/caliciviridae |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |accessdate=9 January 2019 |language=en |format=html}}</ref>\n| subdivision = \n*RHDV [FRG/89] (RHDV-FRG)\n*RCV [ITL/95] (RHDV-RCV)\n*RCV-A1 [MIC-07/2007/AU] (RHDV-RCV-A1)\n*RHDV [Ashington/1998/UK] (RHDV-Ash)\n}}\n[[File:CSIRO ScienceImage 2009 Rabbit Calicivirus.jpg|thumb|Rabbit Calicivirus <small>CSIRO</small>]]\n\n'''Rabbit haemorrhagic disease''' ('''RHD''') is a highly infectious and lethal form of viral hepatitis that affects European rabbits ''(Oryctolagus cuniculus)''. Mortality rates in adult rabbits generally range from 70 to 100 percent.<ref name=Capucci2017>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Cavadini |first2=P. |last3=Schiavitto |first3=M. |last4=Lombardi |first4=G. |last5=Lavazza |first5=A. |title=Increased pathogenicity in rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus type 2 (RHDV2) |journal=Veterinary Record |date=29 April 2017 |volume=180 |issue=17 |page=426 |doi=10.1136/vr.104132}}</ref> The disease is caused by the [[lagovirus]] '''rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus''' ('''RHDV''') in the family [[Caliciviridae]]. The virus infects only rabbits, and has been used in some countries to control feral rabbit populations.\n\n== RHDV and RHDV2 ==\n\nRabbit haemorrhagic disease viruses (RHDV) are single strand RNA viruses in the genus Lagovirus and the family Caliciviridae. In the course of its evolution RHDV split into six distinct genotypes,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kerr |first1=P. J. |last2=Kitchen |first2=A. |last3=Holmes |first3=E. C. |title=Origin and Phylodynamics of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus |journal=Journal of Virology |date=16 September 2009 |volume=83 |issue=23 |pages=12129\u201312138 |doi=10.1128/JVI.01523-09|doi-access=free }}</ref> all of which are highly pathogenic. In addition, non-pathogenic rabbit caliciviruses related to but distinct from RHDV have been identified in Europe and Australia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Fusi |first2=P. |last3=Lavazza |first3=A. |last4=Pacciarini |first4=M.L. |last5=Rossi |first5=C. |title=Detection and preliminary characterization of a new rabbit calicivirus related to rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus but nonpathogenic |journal=Journal of Virology |date=December 1996 |volume=70 |issue=12 |pages=8614-8623}}</ref>\n\nThe two strains of rabbit hemorrhagic disease currently of medical significance are RHDV and RHDV2. RHDV (sometimes referred to as RHDV1, or as classical RHD) only affects adult European rabbits (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''). This virus was first reported in China in 1984,<ref name=Liu1984>{{cite journal |last1=Liu |first1=S.J. |last2=Xue |first2=H.P. |last3=Pu |first3=B.Q. |last4=Qian |first4=N.H. |title=A new viral disease in rabbits |journal=Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Medicine (Xumu yu Shouyi) |date=1984 |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=253-255}}</ref> from which it spread to much of Asia, Europe, Australia, and elsewhere. There have been a few isolated outbreaks of RHDV in the United States and Mexico, but they remained localized and were eradicated.\n\nIn 2010, a new lagovirus with a distinct antigenic profile was identified in France. This virus also caused RHD but behaved differently from RHDV in that it was was able to cause disease in vaccinated and young rabbits as well as in hares ''(Lepus spp.)''.<ref name=Capucci2017 /> All these features strongly suggested that the virus was not derived from RHDV but from some other unknown source.<ref name=Capucci2017 />  The new virus was named rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (RHDV2). RHDV2 is distinct enough from RHDV that the two require different vaccines, which are only partially cross protective. RHDV2 has since spread to the majority of Europe as well as to Australia and Canada.\n\n== History ==\nRabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDV first appeared in the Winter of 1983 in Jiangsu Province of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It was first isolated and characterized by S.J. Liu ''et al''. in 1984.<ref name=Merck>{{cite web | title = A New Viral Disease of Rabbit| work = The Merck Veterinary Manual | year = 2006 | url = http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/171330.htm | accessdate = 2007-06-17 }}</ref> The Chinese outbreak was spread by the [[angora rabbit]], which had originated in [[Europe]]. Fourteen million domesticated rabbits died within nine months in the outbreak.<ref name=IAS>[http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/rabbit_hemorrhagic_disease.pdf Center for Food Security and Public Health]</ref>\n\nFrom China, RHDV spread westward and reached Europe in 1988. The virus has since appeared in Mexico, [[Cuba]], Australia, New Zealand, the United States and Canada.<ref name=Merck/> In 1992, the United Kingdom reported its first case of RHDV in domestic show rabbits. By the late 1990s, RHDV stretched to forty countries and had become [[endemic]] in [[Wild animal|wild]] and [[feral]] rabbit populations in Europe, Australia, New Zealand and [[Cuba]].<ref name=IAS/> In Europe, there was a rapid increase in research into RHD, due to the importance of the commercial breeding of rabbits for meat and fur production.\n\nThe first reported case of RHDV in the United States was in Iowa on March 9, 2000. The affected breeds included [[List of rabbit breeds|Palominos]] and [[Californian rabbit|California Whites]]. By April 6, 25 of the 27 affected rabbits had died of the infection. In order to contain the disease, the remaining two rabbits were euthanized. No new introductions of rabbits were placed on the farm for two years after the discovery of RHDV1 and August 1999 was the last time rabbits left and/or returned to the farm. The United States experienced other outbreaks of RHDV in 2001 ([[Utah]], [[Illinois]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) and 2005 ([[Indiana]]).<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn 2010, a new virus variant called rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (RHDV2) emerged in France.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Le Gall-Recul\u00e9|first=Ghislaine|last2=Lavazza|first2=Antonio|last3=Marchandeau|first3=St\u00e9phane|last4=Bertagnoli|first4=St\u00e9phane|last5=Zwingelstein|first5=Fran\u00e7oise|last6=Cavadini|first6=Patrizia|last7=Martinelli|first7=Nicola|last8=Lombardi|first8=Guerino|last9=Gu\u00e9rin|first9=Jean-Luc|date=2013-09-08|title=Emergence of a new lagovirus related to rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus|journal=Veterinary Research|language=En|volume=44|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-44-81|pmc=3848706|pmid=24011218|pages=81}}</ref> RHDV2 has since spread from France to the rest of Europe, Great Britain, Australia, and New Zealand. Outbreaks of RHDV2 started occurring in the United States and Vancouver Island Canada in 2019. In 2020, RHDV2 has been reported in Washington State, New York, Arizona, New Mexico, and Texas.\n\n== World geographic distribution ==\n===Asia===\nThe first reported outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDV1 occurred in 1984 in the Jiangsu Province of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=Liu1984 />  The outbreak occurred in a group of Angora rabbits that had been imported from Germany. The cause of the disease was determined to be a small non-enveloped RNA virus. An inactivated vaccine was developed from the isolated virus that proved effective in preventing disease.<ref name=Liu1984 /> In less than a year, the disease spread over an area of 50,000 square kilometers in China and killed 140 million domestic rabbits.<ref name=\"Abrantes2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Abrantes|first1=J|last2=van der Loo|first2=W|last3=Le Pendu|first3=J|last4=Esteves|first4=PJ|title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease (RHD) and rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus (RHDV): a review|journal=Veterinary Research|date=10 February 2012|volume=43|pages=12|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-43-12|pmid=22325049|pmc=3331820}}</ref>   [[Republic of Korea|South Korea]] was the next country in Asia to report RHD outbreaks following the importation of rabbit fur from China.<ref name=Abrantes2012 />  RHD has since spread to and become endemic in many countries in Asia, including India and the Middle East.\n\n===Americas (North and South)===\nSince 1993, RHDV1 has been endemic in Cuba; it is also believed to be thriving in [[Bolivia]]. From 1988 to 1992 Mexico dealt with an RHDV1 endemic in domestic rabbits, but was able to quarantine and eradicate the outbreak.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nRHDV1 was unable to establish a foothold in the United States, where ''Oryctolagus cuniculus'' does not occur in the wild.<ref name=IAS/> Species native to the United States [[Eastern cottontail|cottontails]] ''(Sylvilagus floridanus)'', [[black-tailed jackrabbit]]s ''(Lepus californicus)'' and [[volcano rabbit]]s ''(Romerolagus diazzi)'' were not susceptible to RHDV1.<ref name=IAS/> Outbreaks of RHDV1 in domestic populations have occurred in 2000 (Iowa<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit calicivirus infection confirmed in Iowa rabbitry |url=https://www.avma.org/News/JAVMANews/Pages/s051500d.aspx |website=www.avma.org |publisher=American Veterinary Medical Association |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2001 (Utah<ref>{{cite web |title=Viral Hemorrhagic Disease of Rabbits_ Utah 8_28_01 |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_domestic/ct_vhdr_utah0801 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>, Illinois<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Campagnolo |first1=Enzo R. |last2=Ernst |first2=Mark J. |last3=Berniger |first3=Mary L. |last4=Gregg |first4=Douglas A. |last5=Shumaker |first5=Thomas J. |last6=Boghossian |first6=Aida M. |title=Outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease in domestic lagomorphs |journal=Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association |date=October 2003 |volume=223 |issue=8 |pages=1151\u20135 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/9034795 |accessdate=22 June 2019|doi=10.2460/javma.2003.223.1151 |pmid=14584745 }}</ref>, and New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aglearn.usda.gov/customcontent/APHIS/Disposal/FAD/images/rabbitHemo.pdf|title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease (Calicivirus) in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=AgLearn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>) 2005 (Indiana<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease_ Indiana |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_archives/ct_rhdindiana061505 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2008, 2010, and 2018 (Ohio<ref>{{cite web |title=First report of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Type 2 In US found in Ohio |url=https://agri.ohio.gov/wps/portal/gov/oda/programs/animal-disease-diagnostic-lab/news-and-events/Rabbit-Hemorrhagic-Disease-Type-2-Found-In-Ohio |publisher=Ohio Department of Agriculture |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref> and Pennsylvania<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease, United States of America (Jefferson County, Pennsylvania report) |url=http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=28906 |website=OiE |publisher=World Organization for Animal Health |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>). \n\nIn early 2018, the first outbreak of the RHDV2 virus in British Columbia was discovered in feral rabbits on central Vancouver Island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sterritt|first1=Spencer|title=Rare and lethal virus found in deceased Nanaimo rabbits; 1st case in B.C.|url=https://nanaimonewsnow.com/article/570436/rare-and-lethal-virus-found-deceased-nanaimo-rabbits-1st-case-bc|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=NanaimoNewsNOW|date=2 March 2018}}</ref> In July 2019, the Washington State Veterinarian's Office confirmed the first case of RHDV2 in Washington State; the domesticated rabbit was bred on [[Orcas Island]].<ref>{{cite press release |last=McGann |first=Chris |date=19 June 2019 |title=Deadly rabbit disease confirmed on Orcas Island |url=https://agr.wa.gov/about-wsda/news-and-media-relations/news-releases?article=26243 |location=Olympia, WA |publisher=Washington State Department of Agriculture |access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV2 occurred at a veterinary hospital in New York. Thirteen pet rabbits were affected, and all died of the disease. The source of the virus has yet to be identified. <ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease, United States of America |url=https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=33541 |website=www.oie.int |publisher=OIE |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV2 began in New Mexico, Arizona, and Texas that is affecting wild jackrabbit and cottontail populations as well as domestic pet species.  <ref>http://www.wildlife.state.nm.us/rabbit-hemorrhagic-disease-cause-for-rabbit-mortality/</ref> This outbreak is spreading, and is unlikely to be contained. \n\n===Australia===\nIn 1991 a strain of the RHDV1 virus, Czech CAPM 351RHDV, was imported to Australia<ref>{{cite book|title=Australia's War Against Rabbits |last=Cooke |first=Brian Douglas |publisher=CSIRO Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=9780643096127 |url= http://www.publish.csiro.au/pid/6508.htm}}</ref> under strict [[quarantine]] conditions to research the safety and usefulness of the virus if it was used as a [[biological control agent]] against Australia and New Zealand's [[Rabbits in Australia|rabbit pest problem]]. Testing of the virus was undertaken on [[Wardang Island]] in [[Spencer Gulf]] off the coast of the [[Yorke Peninsula]], [[South Australia]]. In 1995 the virus escaped quarantine and subsequently killed 10 million rabbits within 8 weeks of its release.<ref name=strive>{{cite web|url=http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |format=pdf |title=Rabbit Calicivirus Disease (RCD) |last=Strive |first=Tanja |publisher=[[Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]] |date=16 July 2008 |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415081441/http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |archivedate=April 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017 a new Korean strain known as RHDV1 K5 was successfully released in a deliberate manner after almost a decade of research. This strain was chosen in part because it functions better in cool, wet regions where the previous Calicivirus was less effective.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Prue|title=K5 rabbit virus an early success, researchers say|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-04-01/k5-rabbit-virus-an-early-success-csiro-researchers-say/8400816|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn July 1997, after considering over 800 public submissions, the [[New Zealand Ministry of Health]] decided not to allow RHDV to be imported into New Zealand to control rabbit populations. This was backed up in an early August review of the decision by the Director-General of Agriculture. However, in late August it was confirmed that RHDV had been deliberately and illegally introduced to the [[Cromwell, New Zealand|Cromwell]] area of the [[South Island]].\n\nAn unsuccessful attempt was made by New Zealand officials to control the spread of the disease. It was, however, being intentionally spread, and several farmers (notably in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] area) admitted to processing rabbits that had died from the disease in kitchen blenders for further spreading.\n\nHad the disease been introduced at a better time, there would have been a more effective control of the population. However, it was released after breeding had commenced for the season, and rabbits under 2 weeks old at the time of the introduction were resistant to the disease. These young rabbits were therefore able to survive and breed rabbit numbers back up. Ten years on, rabbit populations (in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] in particular) are beginning to reach near pre-plague proportions once again though they have not yet returned to pre RCD levels.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Munro|editor1-first=Robert K. |editor2-last=Williams|editor2-first=Richard T. |title=Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease: Issues in Assessment for biological control |date=1994 |publisher=Bureau of Resource Sciences |location=Canberra |isbn=9780644335126}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Plan for 1080 drops in MacKenzie Basin |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/2441711/Mackenzie-1080-drop-plan |last=Williams |first=David |date=26 May 2009 |newspaper= The Press |accessdate = 2009-06-14}}</ref>\n\nResistance to RHD in New Zealand rabbits has led to the widespread use of [[1080 usage in New Zealand|Compound 1080 (Sodium fluoroacetate)]]. The Government and department of Conservation are having to increase their use of 1080 to protect Reserve land from rabbits and preserve the gains made in recent years through the use of RHD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1080facts.co.nz/ |title=Welcome to 1080: The Facts |publisher=1080facts.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nThe first report of RHDV in Europe came from in Italy in 1986.<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> From there it spread to much of Europe.  Spain's first reported case was in 1988,<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> and France, Belgium, and [[Scandinavia]] followed in 1990. Spain experienced a large die-off of wild rabbits, which in turn caused a population decline in predators that normally ate rabbits, including the [[Iberian lynx]] and [[Spanish imperial eagle]].<ref name=sd110705>{{cite news | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/07/110705081111.htm | title = Iberian Lynx Depends On Rabbits for Survival | publisher = Science Daily | date = 5 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=sa110712>{{cite news | url = http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/extinction-countdown/2011/07/12/deadly-rabbit-disease-may-have-doomed-iberian-lynx/ | title = Deadly Rabbit Disease May Have Doomed Iberian Lynx | first = John R. | last = Platt | work = Scientific American | date = 12 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nRHD caused by RHDV was reported for the first time in the United Kingdom in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chasey |first1=D. |title=Possible origin of rabbit haemorrhagic disease in the United Kingdom |journal=Veterinary Record |date=1994 |volume=135 |issue=21 |pages=469-499}}</ref> This initial epidemic was brought under control in the late 1990s using a combination of vaccination, strict biosecurity, and good husbandry.<ref name=Rocchi2018>{{cite journal |last1=Rocchi |first1=Mara S. |last2=Dagleish |first2=Mark P. |title=Diagnosis and prevention of rabbit viral haemorrhagic disease 2 |journal=In Practice |date=27 January 2018 |volume=40 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201316 |doi=10.1136/inp.k54}}</ref> The new viral strain RHDV2 was first detected in England and Wales in 2014, and soon spread to Scotland and Ireland.<ref name=Rocchi2018 /> \n\nIn April 2016, a highly lethal disease started affecting one of the northernmost feral rabbit populations in the world in [[Helsinki]], Finland. The outbreak has since been identified to be caused by the new RHDV2 strain of the virus, being the first appearance of RHD in the country. Cases of viral transmission to domesticated pet rabbits have been confirmed and vaccinating rabbits has been recommended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evira.fi/elaimet/elainlaakaripalvelut/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille/2016/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille-elokuu-2016/rhd-tauti-todettu-myos-lemmikkikaniinissa-erityisluvallista-rokotetta-saatavilla/|title=RHD-tauti todettu my\u00f6s lemmikkikaniinissa - erityisluvallista rokotetta saatavilla|website=Finnish Food Safety Authority (Finnish)|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n== Transmission ==\nTransmission of RHD occurs by direct contact with an infected animal and [[fomite]]s. Rabbits acquire RHD through oral, nasal or [[conjunctival]] pathways. Urine, feces and respiratory secretions may also shed the virus. The virus may also be carried by the wind. Carriers of the virus may remain infectious for up to a month depending on climate conditions; however, the virus has been known to persist for as little as 2 days and as long as 215 days. An infected carcass or hairs from an infected animal may also transmit RHD. Fomites such as clothing, contaminated food, cages, bedding, feeders and water will also harbour the virus. Even though the virus cannot reproduce in other mammals, predators and scavengers such as foxes, ferrets and some birds can excrete the virus through their faeces after ingesting an infected rabbit carcass. Flies, rabbit fleas, and mosquitoes can also spread the virus between rabbits.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nClimate appears to play a crucial role in the transmission of RHD. In normal conditions, most outbreaks of RHD occur in winter or spring. High temperatures in late spring and summer will considerably reduce the spread of the virus. RHD will also be more prevalent in dry and semi-dry areas than in areas that are relatively cool and humid.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Signs ==\nRHD primarily infects only adult rabbits. In fact, research has shown that rabbits younger than 8 weeks of age are resistant to the virus. The incubation period for the RHD virus is between 1 and 3 days, with death following 1 to 2 days after the infection. There is a wide range of RHD symptoms. Most rabbits will show no signs of external symptoms of RHD.\n\nSymptomatic cases of RHD will display fever, squeals, and often coma leading to death within 12 to 36 hours. In less severe cases, rabbits may display uneasiness, excitement, [[Anorexia (symptom)|anorexia]], swollen eyelids, [[paralysis]], ocular [[haemorrhage]]s, and \"paddling\" or loss of skin. Convulsions may be seen as well. A fatal bloody discharge from the nose has been exhibited along with blood-stained cage floors, though these symptoms may have occurred after death. Rabbits who have recovered from the less severe symptoms usually develop severe [[jaundice]] with weight loss and [[lethargy]]. Diarrhoea, constipation and abdominal cramping are then exhibited right before death a few weeks later.<ref>?</ref>\n\nRHD causes rapid development of [[blood clot]] formation in major organs such as the heart, lungs and kidneys. The clots block blood vessels causing heart and respiratory failure. An infected rabbit that has died from RHD will often have its legs straight out and head over its neck.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nRHD may be indicated when several animals in the herd die after experiencing a fever and lethargy. [[Differential diagnosis]] includes [[pasteurellosis]], [[myxomatosis]], poisoning, heat exhaustion, and ''[[E. coli]]'' or ''[[Clostridium perfringens]]'' type E [[enterotoxemia]].\n\nRabbits that die from RHD are usually in good outward state. However, the most frequent post-mortem lesions are [[necrosis]] of the [[liver]], and [[splenomegaly]]. The liver of RHD rabbits may have a fine reticular pattern of necrosis outline each lobule and maybe yellow, gray or pale in colour. The liver is also usually [[friable]] and swollen. The spleen will be black in colour and also swollen with rounded edges, while the kidneys are dark brown in colour. [[Haemorrhages]] will also be seen many other organs and tissues. The trachea may present a foamy, bloody mucous. [[Enteritis]] of the small intestine and swollen [[meninges]] may also occur.\n\nLaboratory tests such as [[reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction]] (RT-PCR), [[Western blotting]], negative-staining immunoelectron microscopy, and [[ELISA]]s may be performed on samples from the liver, blood, spleen or other organs.\n\n== Morbidity, mortality, and immunity ==\nRHD is extremely hard to locate in the wild since about 75% of rabbits with RHD will die in their burrows underground. Due to this difficulty, the [[morbidity]] and [[Mortality rate|mortality]] estimates for RHD have a broad range. The morbidity rate ranges from 30% to 100% and the mortality rate from 40% to 100%; however, the typical mortality rate is usually around 90%.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn the wild, outbreaks in rabbits vary depending on the season, breeding cycles and geographical location. Some areas will see a high morbidity and mortality among its rabbit populations followed by calmer periods.\n\nMaternal antibodies such as [[immunoglobulin G]] (IgG), which are readily transmitted to the young across the placenta, may explain why very young rabbits are resistant to RHD. Some scientists also believe that the immature immune system of a young rabbit cannot produce the number of chemicals needed to initiate clotting in order to kill. Rabbits may develop immunity against other strains of the RHD virus, while others may endure persistent infections. The immunity does not survive through the next generation, leaving open the possibility of further outbreaks in the population.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marques|first1=Raquel M|last2=Teixeira|first2=Luzia|last3=\u00c1guas|first3=Artur P|last4=Ribeiro|first4=Joana C|last5=Costa-e-Silva|first5=Ant\u00f3nio|last6=Ferreira|first6=Paula G|title=Immunosuppression abrogates resistance of young rabbits to Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease (RHD)|journal=Veterinary Research|date=4 February 2014|volume=45|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-45-14|pmc=3926702|pmid=24490832|pages=14}}</ref>\n\n== Control ==\nCountries that are uninfected by RHD may place restrictions on importation from endemic countries. According to the [[Merck & Co.|Merck]]/[[Merial]] Manual For Pet Health, Home Edition, 2007, RHD is a reportable disease in the United States. If a diagnosis is made by a veterinarian, a notification to the \"appropriate government authorities\" must be made.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nBecause of the highly infectious nature of the disease, strict quarantine is necessary when outbreaks occur. Depopulation, disinfection, surveillance and quarantines are the only way to properly and effectively eradicate the disease. Good disinfectants include 10% [[sodium hydroxide]], 1-2% [[formalin]], 2% One-Stroke Environ, and 10% household [[bleach]]. The RHD virus is resistant to [[ethers]] and [[chloroform]]. Deceased rabbits must be removed immediately and discarded in a safe manner. Surviving rabbits are quarantined or humanely euthanized. Test rabbits may be used to monitor the virus on vaccinated farms.<ref name=\"IAS\" />\n\nThere are several vaccines available against VHD in the UK: Cylap, made by Fort Dodge Animal Health; Lapinject, made by CEVA Animal Health; Anivac, made by Animalcare Ltd and FILAVAC, made by Filavie. All last for 12 months and contain inactivated strains of VHD. A live combination vaccine, Nobivac Myxo-RHD, made by MSD Animal Health, has recently become available. Its active ingredient is a live myxoma-vectored RHD virus strain 009 and it offers a duration of immunity of 1 year against both RHD and [[myxomatosis]].<ref name=\"NOAH Compendium\">[http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html Therapeutic Indication:  For rabbits] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526030329/http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html |date=2013-05-26 }}, National Office of Animal Health rabbit vaccines.{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}.</ref> FILAVAC has been authorised by the VMD in April 2017; it is currently the only vaccine containing both classic and variant strain of VHD virus.<ref>http://www.vmd.defra.gov.uk/ProductInformationDatabase/SPC_Documents/SPC_1170567.DOC</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rabbits in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*New outbreak in Canada reported on Vancouver Island {{Cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/b-c-issues-warning-to-pet-rabbit-owners-as-virus-spreads-to-lower-mainland-1.4587233 | title=B.C. Issues warning to pet rabbit owners as virus spreads to Lower Mainland &#124; CBC News}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Animal_Health_in_the_World/docs/pdf/Disease_cards/RHD.pdf Disease card]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q994732}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease}}\n[[Category:Animal viral diseases]]\n[[Category:Rabbit diseases]]\n[[Category:Hemorrhagic fevers]]\n[[Category: