ent": "Added info about 2020 COVID-19 closure.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bryce_Canyon_National_Park"}
{"title_page": "Matsutar\u014d Kawaguchi", "text_new": "{{Japanese name|Kawaguchi}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Matsutar\u014d Kawaguchi<br>\u5ddd\u53e3 \u677e\u592a\u90ce \n| image       = Kawaguchi Matsutaro.jpg\n| caption     = Matsutar\u014d Kawaguchi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1899|10|1|df=y}}  \n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1985|6|9|1899|10|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = Japan\n| occupation  = Novelist, Screenwriter\n| genre       = \n| movement    = \n| notableworks = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Matsutar\u014d Kawaguchi'''|\u5ddd\u53e3 \u677e\u592a\u90ce|Kawaguchi Matsutar\u014d|1 October 1899 \u2013 9 June 1985}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] novelist, playwright and [[film producer]] active during the [[Sh\u014dwa period]] of Japan.\n\n==Biography==\nKawaguchi was born in the plebeian [[Asakusa]] district of [[Tokyo]] into an impoverished family. He was forced to leave home at the age of 14 to seek employment. He started to write in his spare time, while working at various jobs, which included working in a [[pawn shop]], as a tailor, a policeman and as a postman at one point in his life. He came to be acquainted with author [[Kubota Mantaro]], who encouraged him in his literary efforts.\n\nKawaguchi was arrested in [[Kamakura, Kanagawa]] in 1933, along with fellow literati [[Kume Masao]] and [[Satomi Ton]] for illegal card [[gambling]].\n\nIn 1935, Kawaguchi won the first [[Naoki Prize]] for a [[short story]] titled ''Tsuruhachi Tsurujir\u014d''. He followed this with a serialized [[novel]], ''Aizen Katsura'', a [[melodrama]]tic love story involving a nurse and a doctor, which ran from 1936-1938. The story became a tremendously popular bestseller and gained him considerable fame. It was later made into a movie starring [[Kinuyo Tanaka]] and [[Ken Uehara]], and was the basis of numerous [[television series]].\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Kawaguchi resumed his literary activity, publishing plays and novels. He won the Yoshikawa Eiji Prize for his novel ''Shigurejaya Oriku'', a nostalgic series of episodes involving a prostitute who rose to become a brothel owner.\n\nMany of Kawaguchi's novels were adapted to film, and he was long associated with [[Daiei Motion Picture Company]]. In 1965, he became a member of the Japan Academy of the Arts. He was awarded the [[Order of Culture]] by the Japanese government in 1973. His wife was the movie actress [[Aiko Mimasu]], and his son was actor [[Hiroshi Kawaguchi (actor)|Hiroshi Kawaguchi]].\n\nKawaguchi won the [[Yoshikawa Eiji Prize]] for his novel ''Shigurejaya Oriku'', a nostalgic series of episodes involving a farm girl, sold to a brothel, who rose to become owner of a famous Tokyo teahouse. The story was eventually translated into English by Royall Tyler.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Japanese literature]]\n*[[List of Japanese authors]]\n\n==References==\n* Kawaguchi, Matsutar\u014d. ''Mistress Oriku: Stories from a Tokyo Teahouse''. Tran, Royall Tyler. Tuttle Publishing (2007). {{ISBN|4-8053-0886-9}}\n* Wakashiro, Kiiko. ''Sora yori no koe: Watakushi no Kawaguchi Matsutaro''. Bungei Shunju (1988). {{ISBN|4-16-342800-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/959-matsutaro-kawaguchi J'Lit | Authors : Matsutaro Kawaguchi | Books from Japan] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kawaguchi, Matsutaro}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Japanese male short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese novelists]]\n[[Category:Japanese film producers]]\n[[Category:Asian film producers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Japanese name|Kawaguchi}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Matsutar\u014d Kawaguchi<br>\u5ddd\u53e3 \u677e\u592a\u90ce \n| image       = Kawaguchi Matsutaro.jpg\n| caption     = Matsutar\u014d Kawaguchi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1899|10|1|df=y}}  \n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1985|6|9|1899|10|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = Japan\n| occupation  = Novelist, Screenwriter\n| genre       = \n| movement    = \n| notableworks = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Matsutar\u014d Kawaguchi'''|\u5ddd\u53e3 \u677e\u592a\u90ce|Kawaguchi Matsutar\u014d|1 October 1899 \u2013 9 June 1985}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] novelist, playwright and [[film producer]] active during the [[Sh\u014dwa period]] of Japan.\n\n==Biography==\nKawaguchi was born in the plebeian [[Asakusa]] district of [[Tokyo]] into an impoverished family. He was forced to leave home at the age of 14 to seek employment. He started to write in his spare time, while working at various jobs, which included working in a [[pawn shop]], as a tailor, a policeman and as a postman at one point in his life. He came to be acquainted with author [[Kubota Mantaro]], who encouraged him in his literary efforts.\n\nKawaguchi was arrested in [[Kamakura, Kanagawa]] in 1933, along with fellow literati [[Kume Masao]] and [[Satomi Ton]] for illegal card [[gambling]].\n\nIn 1935, Kawaguchi won the first [[Naoki Prize]] for a [[short story]] titled ''Tsuruhachi Tsurujir\u014d''. He followed this with a serialized [[novel]], ''Aizen Katsura'', a [[melodrama]]tic love story involving a nurse and a doctor, which ran from 1936-1938. The story became a tremendously popular bestseller and gained him considerable fame. It was later made into a movie starring [[Kinuyo Tanaka]] and [[Ken Uehara]], and was the basis of numerous [[television series]].\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Kawaguchi resumed his literary activity, publishing plays and novels. He won the Yoshikawa Eiji Prize for his novel ''Shigurejaya Oriku'', a nostalgic series of episodes involving a prostitute who rose to become a brothel owner.\n\nMany of Kawaguchi's novels were adapted to film, and he was long associated with [[Daiei Motion Picture Company]]. In 1965, he became a member of the Japan Academy of the Arts. He was awarded the [[Order of Culture]] by the Japanese government in 1973. His wife was the movie actress [[Aiko Mimasu]], and his son was actor [[Hiroshi Kawaguchi]].\n\nKawaguchi won the [[Yoshikawa Eiji Prize]] for his novel ''Shigurejaya Oriku'', a nostalgic series of episodes involving a farm girl, sold to a brothel, who rose to become owner of a famous Tokyo teahouse. The story was eventually translated into English by Royall Tyler.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Japanese literature]]\n*[[List of Japanese authors]]\n\n==References==\n* Kawaguchi, Matsutar\u014d. ''Mistress Oriku: Stories from a Tokyo Teahouse''. Tran, Royall Tyler. Tuttle Publishing (2007). {{ISBN|4-8053-0886-9}}\n* Wakashiro, Kiiko. ''Sora yori no koe: Watakushi no Kawaguchi Matsutaro''. Bungei Shunju (1988). {{ISBN|4-16-342800-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/959-matsutaro-kawaguchi J'Lit | Authors : Matsutaro Kawaguchi | Books from Japan] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kawaguchi, Matsutaro}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Japanese male short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese novelists]]\n[[Category:Japanese film producers]]\n[[Category:Asian film producers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese male writers]]\n", "name_user": "DDDnfl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Clarified link for Hiroshi Kawaguchi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matsutar%C5%8D_Kawaguchi"}
{"title_page": "Cricket Wireless", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Cricket Wireless LLC\n| logo             = Cricket_Wireless_Logo.png\n| logo_caption     = \n| image            = \n| image_caption    = \n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|1999|3|17}} in [[Chicago]], Illinois, United States\n| area_served      = United States\n| location_city    = [[Atlanta]], Georgia\n| location_country = United States\n| locations        = 5,000 retail stores<ref name=\"20Years\"/>\n| num_locations_year = 2019\n| key_people       = {{unbulleted list|John Dwyer ([[President (corporate title)|president]])|Tiffany Baehman (vice president and [[chief marketing officer|CMO]])<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=June 4, 2019 |title=Our Team |url=https://www.cricketwireless.com/why-cricket/our-team.html |website=Cricket Wireless}}</ref>}}\n| industry         = Wireless telecommunications\n| products         = {{unbulleted list|[[Wireless]]|[[Mobile phone]]}}\n| services         = [[Wireless communications]]\n| parent           = {{unbulleted list|[[Leap Wireless]] (1999\u20132014)|[[AT&T]] (2014\u2013present)}}\n| homepage         = {{URL|cricketwireless.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Cricket Wireless LLC''', simply known as '''Cricket Wireless''' or '''Cricket''', is a wholly owned [[subsidiary]] of [[AT&T Inc.]], that provides [[wireless services]] to 10 million subscribers in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"20Years\"/> Cricket Wireless was founded in March 1999 by [[Leap Wireless]] International. AT&T acquired Leap Wireless International in March 2014 which merged Cricket Wireless with [[Aio Wireless]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://cricketwireless.mediaroom.com/2019-01-30-Cricket-Wireless-Now-Serving-10-Million-Subscribers |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 30, 2019 |title=Cricket Wireless Now Serving 10 Million Subscribers |location=Atlanta, Georgia |publisher=Cricket Wireless |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> Before AT&T's acquisition, the company had 4.5 million subscribers.\n\n==History==https://cricketupdatesfaster.blogspot.com/\n[[File:Cricket Wireless at Cornell Square - Hillsboro, Oregon.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Typical Cricket retail store in [[Hillsboro, Oregon]]]]\n[[File:Cricket logo.svg|thumbnail|Former Cricket Wireless logo, before acquisition by AT&T]]\n\nCricket's first market was Chattanooga, Tennessee, in 1999 and through much of its early growth became known as a network focused on small, rural markets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-lz1b12leap224820-something-talk-about-2009apr12-story.html |title=Something to talk about |last=Sidener |first=Jonathan |work=San Diego Union Tribune |access-date=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"20Years\">{{cite press release |url=http://cricketwireless.mediaroom.com/news-releases?item=122663 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 11, 2019 |title=Cricket Wireless Is Turning 20. Let the Celebrations Begin. |location=Atlanta, Georgia |publisher=Cricket Wireless |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, [[Metro by T-Mobile|MetroPCS]], Cricket Wireless's competing carrier at the time, announced a $5.3 billion bid to merge with Leap Wireless.<ref>{{cite news |title=MetroPCS bids $5.3 billion for Leap Wireless |publisher=Reuters |date = September 4, 2007 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/technology-media-telco-SP/idUSN0439256020070904  |accessdate = May 9, 2008 |first=Caroline |last=Humer}}</ref> Leap informally rejected the bid less than two weeks later.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leap Rejects MetroPCS Merger Offer |publisher=TheStreet.com |date=September 16, 2007 |url=http://www.thestreet.com/newsanalysis/techtelecom/10379784.html |accessdate=May 9, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108163620/http://www.thestreet.com/newsanalysis/techtelecom/10379784.html |archive-date=January 8, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> MetroPCS officially withdrew the bid less than two months later.<ref>{{cite web |last = Dano |first = Mike |title = Metro ditches bid for Leap |publisher=RCR Wireless News |date=November 1, 2007 | url =http://www.rcrnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071101/FREE/71101006/1002/rss01 |accessdate=May 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl =https://archive.is/20071105013450/http://www.rcrnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071101/FREE/71101006/1002/rss01 |archivedate = November 5, 2007}}</ref> In December 2007, Cricket acquired [[Hargray]] Communications Group's wireless telecommunications business.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=191722&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1205151 |title=Leap Wireless \u2013 Media Relations \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date= |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, Cricket and MetroPCS entered into a 10-year roaming agreement covering both companies' existing and future markets. The companies also entered into a spectrum exchange agreement covering licenses in certain markets.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=191722&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1203113 |title=Leap Wireless \u2013 Media Relations \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date= |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> In November 2008, they launched \"Premium Extended Coverage\", a roaming partnership with 14 wireless companies.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=191722&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1226044 |title=Leap Wireless \u2013 Media Relations \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date=2008-11-13 |accessdate=2009-08-27}}</ref> In August 2010, Cricket and [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]] signed a five-year wholesale agreement ([[MVNO]]) which allowed Cricket to utilize Sprint's nationwide [[3G]] EVDO network in the United States.\n\nIn July 2013, AT&T agreed to buy Cricket Wireless' parent for $1.2 billion. The FCC approved the acquisition between AT&T and Leap Wireless in March 2014.<ref name=\"FCC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/3/13/5505798/fcc-approves-att-purchase-of-leap-wireless|title=FCC approves AT&T's purchase of Leap Wireless, says it's 'in the public interest'|last=Welch|first=Chris|work=The Verge|date=March 13, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Coverage network ==\nPrior to its acquisition by AT&T, Cricket's [[CDMA]] network used its home network and roaming agreements with [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]], among other CDMA carriers. However, Cricket's CDMA network was shut down and the spectrum was reframed for use on AT&T's HSPA+ and LTE networks. Following the acquisition by AT&T, Cricket Wireless released devices that use AT&T's 3G, 4G, and 4G LTE networks.\n\nCricket Wireless noted on their old website that CDMA service would be terminated as early as September 2015. Most devices prior to the merger would not be compatible on the GSM network except the iPhone 4s, iPhone 5, iPhone 5c, and iPhone 5s. Compatible iPhone devices would only require a new SIM card.\n\n==Controversies==\n===STARTTLS stripping attack===\nIn October 2014, Cricket Wireless (and its parent company, AT&T Inc.) came under scrutiny for intercepting and modifying its customers' email traffic to downgrade and prevent encryption of the conversation and its metadata.<ref name=\"washingtonPost-tls\">{{cite news |last1=Scola |first1=Nancy |last2=Soltani |first2=Ashkan |date=2014-09-28 |title=Mobile ISP Cricket was thwarting encrypted emails, researchers find |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/10/28/mobile-isp-thwarted-customers-attempts-to-send-encrypted-e-mails-research-finds/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref> An engineer at a digital security and privacy firm, Golden Frog, first noticed the issue in September 2013 via their [[Aio Wireless]] connection (later acquired by Cricket).<ref name=\"goldenFrog-tls\">{{cite web |date=2014-11-04 |title=The FCC Must Prevent ISPs From Blocking Encryption |url=https://www.goldenfrog.com/blog/fcc-must-prevent-isps-blocking-encryption |website=Golden Frog |access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref> Upon further investigation by the privacy firm in June 2014, Golden Frog determined that Cricket [[Opportunistic TLS#Weaknesses and mitigations|masked the STARTTLS command]] in email server responses, thereby \"putting its customers at serious risk by inhibiting their ability to protect online communications.\"<ref name=\"goldenFrog-tls\" /> In October, a ''Washington Post'' investigation revealed that \"Cricket did not address repeated questions about the issue and did not alert customers, many of whom rely on Cricket as their sole Internet service, that they would not be able to protect their e-mails from prying eyes. AT&T, which absorbed Cricket when it acquired Leap Wireless that spring, did not respond to a request for comment.\"<ref name=\"washingtonPost-tls\" /> The EFF also published a technical analysis condemning ISPs like Cricket from tampering with customer internet traffic.<ref>{{cite web |date=2014-11-11 |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/11/starttls-downgrade-attacks |title=ISPs Removing Their Customers' Email Encryption |website=Electronic Frontier Foundation |last=Hoffman-Andrews</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AT&T Mobility]], another subsidiary of AT&T\n* [[AT&T Prepaid|AT&T PREPAID]], AT&T Mobility's prepaid service\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cricketwireless.com/}}\n* [http://cricketwireless.mediaroom.com/ Cricket Newsroom]\n\n{{AT&T}}\n{{Prepaid wireless providers}}\n{{US mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:AT&T subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:2014 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Cricket Wireless LLC\n| logo             = Cricket_Wireless_Logo.png\n| logo_caption     = \n| image            = \n| image_caption    = \n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|1999|3|17}} in [[Chicago]], Illinois, United States\n| area_served      = United States\n| location_city    = [[Atlanta]], Georgia\n| location_country = United States\n| locations        = 5,000 retail stores<ref name=\"20Years\"/>\n| num_locations_year = 2019\n| key_people       = {{unbulleted list|John Dwyer ([[President (corporate title)|president]])|Tiffany Baehman (vice president and [[chief marketing officer|CMO]])<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=June 4, 2019 |title=Our Team |url=https://www.cricketwireless.com/why-cricket/our-team.html |website=Cricket Wireless}}</ref>}}\n| industry         = Wireless telecommunications\n| products         = {{unbulleted list|[[Wireless]]|[[Mobile phone]]}}\n| services         = [[Wireless communications]]\n| parent           = {{unbulleted list|[[Leap Wireless]] (1999\u20132014)|[[AT&T]] (2014\u2013present)}}\n| homepage         = {{URL|cricketwireless.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Cricket Wireless LLC''', simply known as '''Cricket Wireless''' or '''Cricket''', is a wholly owned [[subsidiary]] of [[AT&T Inc.]], that provides [[wireless services]] to 10 million subscribers in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"20Years\"/> Cricket Wireless was founded in March 1999 by [[Leap Wireless]] International. AT&T acquired Leap Wireless International in March 2014 which merged Cricket Wireless with [[Aio Wireless]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://cricketwireless.mediaroom.com/2019-01-30-Cricket-Wireless-Now-Serving-10-Million-Subscribers |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 30, 2019 |title=Cricket Wireless Now Serving 10 Million Subscribers |location=Atlanta, Georgia |publisher=Cricket Wireless |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> Before AT&T's acquisition, the company had 4.5 million subscribers.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cricket Wireless at Cornell Square - Hillsboro, Oregon.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Typical Cricket retail store in [[Hillsboro, Oregon]]]]\n[[File:Cricket logo.svg|thumbnail|Former Cricket Wireless logo, before acquisition by AT&T]]\n\nCricket's first market was Chattanooga, Tennessee, in 1999 and through much of its early growth became known as a network focused on small, rural markets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-lz1b12leap224820-something-talk-about-2009apr12-story.html |title=Something to talk about |last=Sidener |first=Jonathan |work=San Diego Union Tribune |access-date=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"20Years\">{{cite press release |url=http://cricketwireless.mediaroom.com/news-releases?item=122663 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 11, 2019 |title=Cricket Wireless Is Turning 20. Let the Celebrations Begin. |location=Atlanta, Georgia |publisher=Cricket Wireless |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, [[Metro by T-Mobile|MetroPCS]], Cricket Wireless's competing carrier at the time, announced a $5.3 billion bid to merge with Leap Wireless.<ref>{{cite news |title=MetroPCS bids $5.3 billion for Leap Wireless |publisher=Reuters |date = September 4, 2007 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/technology-media-telco-SP/idUSN0439256020070904  |accessdate = May 9, 2008 |first=Caroline |last=Humer}}</ref> Leap informally rejected the bid less than two weeks later.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leap Rejects MetroPCS Merger Offer |publisher=TheStreet.com |date=September 16, 2007 |url=http://www.thestreet.com/newsanalysis/techtelecom/10379784.html |accessdate=May 9, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108163620/http://www.thestreet.com/newsanalysis/techtelecom/10379784.html |archive-date=January 8, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> MetroPCS officially withdrew the bid less than two months later.<ref>{{cite web |last = Dano |first = Mike |title = Metro ditches bid for Leap |publisher=RCR Wireless News |date=November 1, 2007 | url =http://www.rcrnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071101/FREE/71101006/1002/rss01 |accessdate=May 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl =https://archive.is/20071105013450/http://www.rcrnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071101/FREE/71101006/1002/rss01 |archivedate = November 5, 2007}}</ref> In December 2007, Cricket acquired [[Hargray]] Communications Group's wireless telecommunications business.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=191722&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1205151 |title=Leap Wireless \u2013 Media Relations \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date= |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, Cricket and MetroPCS entered into a 10-year roaming agreement covering both companies' existing and future markets. The companies also entered into a spectrum exchange agreement covering licenses in certain markets.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=191722&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1203113 |title=Leap Wireless \u2013 Media Relations \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date= |accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> In November 2008, they launched \"Premium Extended Coverage\", a roaming partnership with 14 wireless companies.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=191722&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1226044 |title=Leap Wireless \u2013 Media Relations \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date=2008-11-13 |accessdate=2009-08-27}}</ref> In August 2010, Cricket and [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]] signed a five-year wholesale agreement ([[MVNO]]) which allowed Cricket to utilize Sprint's nationwide [[3G]] EVDO network in the United States.\n\nIn July 2013, AT&T agreed to buy Cricket Wireless' parent for $1.2 billion. The FCC approved the acquisition between AT&T and Leap Wireless in March 2014.<ref name=\"FCC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/3/13/5505798/fcc-approves-att-purchase-of-leap-wireless|title=FCC approves AT&T's purchase of Leap Wireless, says it's 'in the public interest'|last=Welch|first=Chris|work=The Verge|date=March 13, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Coverage network ==\nPrior to its acquisition by AT&T, Cricket's [[CDMA]] network used its home network and roaming agreements with [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]], among other CDMA carriers. However, Cricket's CDMA network was shut down and the spectrum was reframed for use on AT&T's HSPA+ and LTE networks. Following the acquisition by AT&T, Cricket Wireless released devices that use AT&T's 3G, 4G, and 4G LTE networks.\n\nCricket Wireless noted on their old website that CDMA service would be terminated as early as September 2015. Most devices prior to the merger would not be compatible on the GSM network except the iPhone 4s, iPhone 5, iPhone 5c, and iPhone 5s. Compatible iPhone devices would only require a new SIM card.\n\n==Controversies==\n===STARTTLS stripping attack===\nIn October 2014, Cricket Wireless (and its parent company, AT&T Inc.) came under scrutiny for intercepting and modifying its customers' email traffic to downgrade and prevent encryption of the conversation and its metadata.<ref name=\"washingtonPost-tls\">{{cite news |last1=Scola |first1=Nancy |last2=Soltani |first2=Ashkan |date=2014-09-28 |title=Mobile ISP Cricket was thwarting encrypted emails, researchers find |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/10/28/mobile-isp-thwarted-customers-attempts-to-send-encrypted-e-mails-research-finds/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref> An engineer at a digital security and privacy firm, Golden Frog, first noticed the issue in September 2013 via their [[Aio Wireless]] connection (later acquired by Cricket).<ref name=\"goldenFrog-tls\">{{cite web |date=2014-11-04 |title=The FCC Must Prevent ISPs From Blocking Encryption |url=https://www.goldenfrog.com/blog/fcc-must-prevent-isps-blocking-encryption |website=Golden Frog |access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref> Upon further investigation by the privacy firm in June 2014, Golden Frog determined that Cricket [[Opportunistic TLS#Weaknesses and mitigations|masked the STARTTLS command]] in email server responses, thereby \"putting its customers at serious risk by inhibiting their ability to protect online communications.\"<ref name=\"goldenFrog-tls\" /> In October, a ''Washington Post'' investigation revealed that \"Cricket did not address repeated questions about the issue and did not alert customers, many of whom rely on Cricket as their sole Internet service, that they would not be able to protect their e-mails from prying eyes. AT&T, which absorbed Cricket when it acquired Leap Wireless that spring, did not respond to a request for comment.\"<ref name=\"washingtonPost-tls\" /> The EFF also published a technical analysis condemning ISPs like Cricket from tampering with customer internet traffic.<ref>{{cite web |date=2014-11-11 |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/11/starttls-downgrade-attacks |title=ISPs Removing Their Customers' Email Encryption |website=Electronic Frontier Foundation |last=Hoffman-Andrews</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AT&T Mobility]], another subsidiary of AT&T\n* [[AT&T Prepaid|AT&T PREPAID]], AT&T Mobility's prepaid service\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cricketwireless.com/}}\n* [http://cricketwireless.mediaroom.com/ Cricket Newsroom]\n\n{{AT&T}}\n{{Prepaid wireless providers}}\n{{US mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:AT&T subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:2014 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "Shivam varanasi", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\