{"title_page": "Washington Square (Bangkok)", "text_new": "{{short description|Area in Bangkok, Thailand}}\n'''Washington Square''' was an entertainment area in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], located for many years at [[Sukhumvit Road|Sukhumvit]] [[Soi]] 22, near the [[Phrom Phong Station|Phrom Phong skytrain station]]. It contained bars, restaurants, [[massage parlors]] and a [[katoey]] theatre. Popular mainly with Bangkok expatriates, Middle East oil field workers and older, male, white Americans including many Vietnam War veterans,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlisle |first1=Peter |title=Washington Square Demolition Leaves Bangkok\u2019s Elderly Sexpats Lost, Confused |url=https://thailand-construction.com/1398-washington-square-demolition-leaves-bangkoks-elderly-sexpats-lost-confused/ |website=Thailand Construction and Engineering News |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=7 October 2012}}</ref> ''Bourbon Street'' was well known for serving [[Cajun]] and [[Louisiana Creole people|Creole]] food and was written up by the ''Bangkok Post'' in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=Louisiana's twin cuisines |work=The Bangkok Post |date=20 May 2005}}</ref>  \n\nThe area features in [[Christopher G. Moore]]'s series of crime novels about private eye [[Vincent Calvino]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Christopher G. |title=Paying Back Jack |date=2010 |publisher=Atlantic Books |isbn=978-0-85789-249-2 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sYYiNJLYsukC&pg=PT196&lpg=PT196&dq=washington+square+bangkok++Christopher+G.+Moore&source=bl&ots=L3HPXSpZgo&sig=ACfU3U1HZadHy2BskeESx9Z1yomjaiHP7w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjF1sW94vfoAhVLT8AKHTPKDN4Q6AEwCHoECAsQLw#v=onepage&q=washington%20square%20&f=false |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Christopher G. |title=Spirit House |date=2008 |publisher=Open Road + Grove/Atlantic |isbn=978-1-55584-868-2 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ltkr7HNM1gUC&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=washington+square+bangkok++Christopher+G.+Moore&source=bl&ots=w0Y9C7Q83Q&sig=ACfU3U0qY8-MDqkP1EBuSesQbvpOsk8Yyg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjF1sW94vfoAhVLT8AKHTPKDN4Q6AEwB3oECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=washington%20square%20bangkok%20%20Christopher%20G.%20Moore&f=false |language=en |chapter=6. Washington Square}}</ref> and the Texas Lone Staar bar was often mentioned in the mystery novels of [[Dean Barrett]], who once rented an apartment in the Square.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barrett |first1=Dean |title=Farewell to Washington Square |url=https://www.stickmanbangkok.com/readers-submissions/2013/04/farewell-to-washington-square/ |website=Stickman Bangkok |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nWashington Square was completely demolished in 2013, pending the construction of a shopping mall and several high rise buildings. The restaurants and a few of the bars have relocated elsewhere on Sukhumit Road, but most have simply closed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cole |first1=Carleton |title=Bygone era of bars gone by |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/life/social-and-lifestyle/383728/bygone-era-of-bars-gone-by |website=www.bangkokpost.com |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=8 December 2013}}</ref> The Emporium group's plan to build a shopping mall called EmSphere was put on hold. A dinosaur [[theme park]] was established on the site in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Is EmSphere Being Put On Hold For A Dinosaur Park? |url=https://whatsonsukhumvit.com/is-emsphere-shopping-mall-being-put-on-hold-for-a-dinosaur-theme-park/ |website=WOS |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=2 March 2016}}</ref> The theme park closed in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fire at closed Dinosaur Planet theme park |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/thailand/general/1458258/fire-at-closed-dinosaur-planet-theme-park |website=www.bangkokpost.com |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{sex-stub}}\n\n{{coord|13|43|55|N|100|33|58|E|type:landmark|display=title}}\n \n[[Category:Neighbourhoods of Bangkok]]\t\n[[Category:Red-light districts in Thailand]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Area in Bangkok, Thailand}}\n'''Washington Square''' was an entertainment area in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], located for many years at [[Sukhumvit Road|Sukhumvit]] [[Soi]] 22, near the [[Phrom Phong Station|Phrom Phong skytrain station]]. It contained bars, restaurants, [[massage parlors]] and a [[katoey]] theatre. Popular mainly with Bangkok expatriates, Middle East oil field workers and older, male, white Americans including many Vietnam War veterans,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlisle |first1=Peter |title=Washington Square Demolition Leaves Bangkok\u2019s Elderly Sexpats Lost, Confused |url=https://thailand-construction.com/1398-washington-square-demolition-leaves-bangkoks-elderly-sexpats-lost-confused/ |website=Thailand Construction and Engineering News |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=7 October 2012}}</ref> ''Bourbon Street'' was well known for serving [[Cajun]] and [[Louisiana Creole people|Creole]] food and was written up by the ''Bangkok Post'' in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=Louisiana's twin cuisines |work=The Bangkok Post |date=20 May 2005}}</ref>  \n\nThe area features in [[Christopher G. Moore]]'s series of crime novels about private eye [[Vincent Calvino]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Christopher G. |title=Paying Back Jack |date=2010 |publisher=Atlantic Books |isbn=978-0-85789-249-2 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sYYiNJLYsukC&pg=PT196&lpg=PT196&dq=washington+square+bangkok++Christopher+G.+Moore&source=bl&ots=L3HPXSpZgo&sig=ACfU3U1HZadHy2BskeESx9Z1yomjaiHP7w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjF1sW94vfoAhVLT8AKHTPKDN4Q6AEwCHoECAsQLw#v=onepage&q=washington%20square%20&f=false |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Christopher G. |title=Spirit House |date=2008 |publisher=Open Road + Grove/Atlantic |isbn=978-1-55584-868-2 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ltkr7HNM1gUC&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=washington+square+bangkok++Christopher+G.+Moore&source=bl&ots=w0Y9C7Q83Q&sig=ACfU3U0qY8-MDqkP1EBuSesQbvpOsk8Yyg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjF1sW94vfoAhVLT8AKHTPKDN4Q6AEwB3oECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=washington%20square%20bangkok%20%20Christopher%20G.%20Moore&f=false |language=en |chapter=6. Washington Square}}</ref> and the Texas Lone Staar bar was often mentioned in the mystery novels of [[Dean Barrett]], who once rented an apartment in the Square.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barrett |first1=Dean |title=Farewell to Washington Square |url=https://www.stickmanbangkok.com/readers-submissions/2013/04/farewell-to-washington-square/ |website=Stickman Bangkok |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nWashington Square was completely demolished in 2013, pending the construction of a shopping mall and several high rise buildings. The restaurants and a few of the bars have relocated elsewhere on Sukhumit Road, but most have simply closed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cole |first1=Carleton |title=Bygone era of bars gone by |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/life/social-and-lifestyle/383728/bygone-era-of-bars-gone-by |website=www.bangkokpost.com |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=8 December 2013}}</ref> The Emporium group's plan to build a shopping mall called EmSphere was was put on hold. A dinosaur [[theme park]] was established on the site in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Is EmSphere Being Put On Hold For A Dinosaur Park? |url=https://whatsonsukhumvit.com/is-emsphere-shopping-mall-being-put-on-hold-for-a-dinosaur-theme-park/ |website=WOS |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=2 March 2016}}</ref> The theme park closed in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fire at closed Dinosaur Planet theme park |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/thailand/general/1458258/fire-at-closed-dinosaur-planet-theme-park |website=www.bangkokpost.com |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{sex-stub}}\n\n{{coord|13|43|55|N|100|33|58|E|type:landmark|display=title}}\n \n[[Category:Neighbourhoods of Bangkok]]\t\n[[Category:Red-light districts in Thailand]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_Square_(Bangkok)"}
{"title_page": "Bye Bye Birdie (1995 film)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{No plot|date=April 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''Bye Bye Birdie''' is a 1995 [[television film]] produced by [[Sonar Entertainment|RHI Entertainment]] based on the 1960 [[Bye Bye Birdie|stage musical]] by [[Charles Strouse]], [[Lee Adams]], and [[Michael Stewart (playwright)|Michael Stewart]]. The musical had previously been made into a [[Bye Bye Birdie (film)|film in 1963]]. \n\nThe TV movie, which was broadcast by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], won an [[Emmy Award]] in 1996 for Outstanding Music and Lyrics, and was nominated for Outstanding Music Direction and Outstanding Hairstyling for a Miniseries or a Special.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bye Bye Birdie |url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/bye-bye-birdie |website=Television Academy (Emmys.com) |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Jason Alexander]] - Albert J. Peterson  \n*[[Vanessa Williams]] - Rose Alvarez  \n*[[Chynna Phillips]] - Kim MacAfee  \n*[[Tyne Daly]] - Mae Peterson  \n*[[Marc Kudisch]] - Conrad Birdie  \n*[[George Wendt]] - Harry MacAfee  \n*[[Sally Mayes]] - Doris MacAfee  \n*[[Jason Gaffney]] - Hugo F. Peabody  \n*[[Blair Slater]] - Randolph MacAfee  \n*[[Vicki Lewis]] - Gloria Rasputin  \n*[[Brigitta Dau]] - Ursula Merkle  \n*[[Angela Brydon]] - Sad Face Girl  \n*[[Shelley S. Hunt]] - Alice  \n*[[Marlowe Gardiner-Heslin]] - Suzie(as Marlowe Windsor-Menard)  \n*[[Brenna Quan]] - Penelope-Ann  \n*[[Angela Quinn]] - Debra Sue  \n*[[Debbie Timuss]] - Nancy  \n*[[Julie Tomaino]] - Margie  \n*[[Chiara Zanni]] - Helen  \n*[[Kristian Ayre]] - Harvey Johnson  \n*[[Duane Keogh]] - Freddie  \n*[[Chancz Perry]] - Karl  \n*[[Jay Brazeau]] - Mayor  \n*[[Nicole Robert]] - Mayor's Wife (Edna)  \n*[[Garry Chalk]] - Maude  \n*[[Ian Capper McIntyre]] - Mr. Johnson (as Capper McIntyrre)  \n*[[Sheelah Megill]] - Mrs. Merkle   \n*[[Suzanne Ristic]] - Mary\n\n==Songs==\n*Main Title (Bye Bye Birdie) - The Teens\n*An English Teacher - Vanessa Williams\n*The Telephone Hour - The Teens\n*How Lovely To Be A Woman - Chynna Phillips\n*Put On a Happy Face - Jason Alexander\n*A Healthy, Normal American Boy - Vanessa Williams\n*One Boy - Chynna Phillips\n*Let's Settle Down - Vanessa Williams\n*Honestly Sincere - Marc Kudisch\n*Hymn for a Sunday Evening (Ed Sullivan) - Sally Mayes\n*One Last Kiss - Marc Kudisch\n*What Did I Ever See In Him - Vanessa Williams\n*A Lot of Livin' to Do - Marc Kudisch\n*Kids - Sally Mayes\n*Spanish Rose - Vanessa Williams\n*Talk To Me - Jason Alexander\n*A Mother Doesn't Matter Anymore - Tyne Daly\n*A Giant Step - Jason Alexander\n*Rosie - Vanessa Williams\n*End Credits (Bye Bye Birdie) - Chynna Phillips\n\n==Further reading==\n* \"[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1995/12/01/075698.html TV Weekend: 50's Revisited in New 'Bye Bye Birdie]\" by John J. O'Connor, ''[[The New York Times]]'' (Dec 1, 1995) \n* \"[https://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/bye-bye-birdie-3-1200444227/ Bye Bye Birdie review]\" by Jeremy Gerard, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (Dec 3, 1995)\n* \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-12-03-tv-9654-story.html 'Bye Bye Birdie' Spreads Its Wings on ABC]\" by Susan King, ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' (Dec 3, 1995)\n* \"[https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/1995-bye-bye-birdie-film-with-jason-alexander_87751.html 1995 Bye Bye Birdie, With Jason Alexander and Vanessa Williams, on BroadwayHD]\", ''Theatermania'' (Feb 7, 2019)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|tt0112605|Bye Bye Birdie}}\n\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:Television musicals]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{No plot|date=April 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''Bye Bye Birdie''' is a 1995 [[television film]] produced by [[Sonar Entertainment|RHI Entertainment]] based on the 1960 [[Bye Bye Birdie|stage musical]] by [[Charles Strouse]], [[Lee Adams]], and [[Michael Stewart (playwright)|Michael Stewart]]. The musical had previously been made into a [[Bye Bye Birdie (film)|film in 1963]]. \n\nThe TV movie, which broadcast by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], won an [[Emmy Award]] in 1996 for Outstanding Music and Lyrics, and was nominated for Outstanding Music Direction and Outstanding Hairstyling for a Miniseries or a Special.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bye Bye Birdie |url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/bye-bye-birdie |website=Television Academy (Emmys.com) |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Jason Alexander]] - Albert J. Peterson  \n*[[Vanessa Williams]] - Rose Alvarez  \n*[[Chynna Phillips]] - Kim MacAfee  \n*[[Tyne Daly]] - Mae Peterson  \n*[[Marc Kudisch]] - Conrad Birdie  \n*[[George Wendt]] - Harry MacAfee  \n*[[Sally Mayes]] - Doris MacAfee  \n*[[Jason Gaffney]] - Hugo F. Peabody  \n*[[Blair Slater]] - Randolph MacAfee  \n*[[Vicki Lewis]] - Gloria Rasputin  \n*[[Brigitta Dau]] - Ursula Merkle  \n*[[Angela Brydon]] - Sad Face Girl  \n*[[Shelley S. Hunt]] - Alice  \n*[[Marlowe Gardiner-Heslin]] - Suzie(as Marlowe Windsor-Menard)  \n*[[Brenna Quan]] - Penelope-Ann  \n*[[Angela Quinn]] - Debra Sue  \n*[[Debbie Timuss]] - Nancy  \n*[[Julie Tomaino]] - Margie  \n*[[Chiara Zanni]] - Helen  \n*[[Kristian Ayre]] - Harvey Johnson  \n*[[Duane Keogh]] - Freddie  \n*[[Chancz Perry]] - Karl  \n*[[Jay Brazeau]] - Mayor  \n*[[Nicole Robert]] - Mayor's Wife (Edna)  \n*[[Garry Chalk]] - Maude  \n*[[Ian Capper McIntyre]] - Mr. Johnson (as Capper McIntyrre)  \n*[[Sheelah Megill]] - Mrs. Merkle   \n*[[Suzanne Ristic]] - Mary\n\n==Songs==\n*Main Title (Bye Bye Birdie) - The Teens\n*An English Teacher - Vanessa Williams\n*The Telephone Hour - The Teens\n*How Lovely To Be A Woman - Chynna Phillips\n*Put On a Happy Face - Jason Alexander\n*A Healthy, Normal American Boy - Vanessa Williams\n*One Boy - Chynna Phillips\n*Let's Settle Down - Vanessa Williams\n*Honestly Sincere - Marc Kudisch\n*Hymn for a 